<h3>Smiling At Strangers on Trains</h3>

<p><div class="box">
	It was the strangest thing today:<br>
	I saw new footprints in abandoned pathways.<br>
	Beneath forgotten undergrowth something stirring again <br>
	You were a single red blood cell but I lost you in the knot of capillaries,<br>
	<b>But you were bringing me oxygen when I needed it most in the smoke.</b><br>
	<br>
	And you were always as far as Mongolia,<br>
	As close as my clothes,<br>
	Your presence pervading,<br>
	But it still never shows.<br>
	<b>As close as the answer I never quite know,<br>
	Or can't quite remember.</b><br>
	Your distance insidious,<br>
	As soft as a blow.<br>
	<b>Your shadow is with me wherever I go.<br>
	It's on the tip of my tongue but still I never quite know,<br>
	Or can't quite remember.</b><br>
	I don't quite remember.<br>
	<br>
	The forced proximity of a million different Mike Leigh movies<br>
	Makes me long for the fresh air of a familiar face,<br>
	<b>And not the violence of loneliness,</b><br>
	Nor the unease of surrounded seclusion.<br>
	<b>I keep nearly missing you around corners and in passing trains.<br>
	<br>
	And if I'd known that you weren't so far away,<br>
	That you were never that far away,<br>
	I could've rode this train smiling.</b>
</div></p>

<h4>Thoughts:</h4>

<p>This is currently my favorite song.</p>
<p>This song is a cover of the first single from Frank Turner's old band, Million Dead. That band was post-hardcore, though. I heard the original, and I frankly don't like it as much.</p>
<p>Frank Turner's a sort of acoustic punk folk musician, and I just find so much more emotion in this cover than anything by Million Dead.</p>
<p>I've been listening to this song straight for hours upon hours, and the rhythm of the song, both with the flow of the vocals and the guitar/drums that make up the harmony are making me absolutely obsessed.</p>